The three "holes" are the result of the 3 [ carpels
](https://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gynoecium#Carpels) in coconut flowers, and
three carpels is typical of the family [ Arecaceae
](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Arecaceae) (Palms). The "holes" are actually
germination pores, where one is usually functional and the other two are
plugged. The new coconunt shoot will emerge from the functional, open,
germination pore.

For further info and pictures, see [ this webpage
](http://waynesword.palomar.edu/ecoph10.htm) or the paper [ _Morphological and
anatomical studies of the coconut_
](https://www.google.se/url?sa=t&source=web&rct=j&url=http://edepot.wur.nl/288905&ved=2ahUKEwjhtabQvJLaAhWjE5oKHa1nDCIQFjACegQIBxAB&usg=AOvVaw2n-iXvGR_sbOtuSCUJMzzq)
(Smit 1970, link to pdf), which holds a wealth of information.
